metadata.name: Equilibrium #94
metadata.description: Equilibrium shows the algorithm in its search for balance in color and composition. It symbolizes how, at its core, generative art itself is the act of balancing constraints and freedom, consistency and variation, predictability and surprise. Based on empirical data, all mints should eventually converge to a stable state, though this is not guaranteed mathematically. Implemented in 5121 hand-crafted characters of JS code. Forever limited to 100 unique editions living on the Tezos blockchain. London - December 2021.

metadata.name: Tympanic #164
metadata.description:
Tympanic is a companion piece to Euphonic [https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10982] and is released as a free gift to all collectors of Euphonic.

Like Euphonic, this piece attempts to play with the idea of interference and emergent patterns, but this time does so by using pixelation instead of Moire. In this way, where Euphonic was about emergent melodies, Tympanic is about emergent rhythms.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: hollow #177
metadata.description:
In 1993, Basque sculptor Eduardo Chillida proposed a project to create an immense void inside Tindaya, the Sacred Mountain of Fuerteventura's indigenous inhabitants. The hollow cube measuring approximately 45 x 50 x 65 meters was conceived as a space for "all the people" to "fully experience the tininess of humankind".

The idea of the project dates back to the 1980s, and it took the artist years of searching for the ideal mountain in different parts of the world. However, what was ideal for Chillida evoked a lot of controversy due to the environmental and social impact of the project. There was uncertainty about Tindaya's structural feasibility and the potential harm to the ancient petroglyphs engraved on its surface. What's more, the financial sustainability of the project's economic model would depend on hundreds of thousands of tourists visiting the site each year, converting a work of art into a holiday attraction.

Chillida called his project the Monument to Tolerance. Although it never came into existence, it has caused division and conflict since it was conceived.


"hollow" is an exploration of 256 voids in nonexistent natural monuments. Made of digital matter instead of stone and lacking cultural charge, its sole purpose is to contemplate the tininess of humankind.


-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.

Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image. 

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. I tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

-----

Possible features:

color scheme: cairngorm, alborz, bardenas, atlas, bieszczady, watkins

proportions: square, wide, standard, narrow

frame: none, vignette, bright, dark, bright with vignette, dark with vignette

visitors: tourists, tourists and birds, solitary flock of birds, only light

metadata.name: Polyptych #49
metadata.description:
Polyptych is a 3D interactive installation inspired by generative plotter designs. It is also meant to be displayed as multiple prints taken from different angles, be it a diptych, triptych, tetraptych, or more.

For an example see: https://bgo.la/polyptych.png

Instructions:

- use the mouse to navigate around the piece (zoom, pan and drag)
- press 'c' to switch between multiple camera angles
- press 'space' to pause the animation
- press 'p' to take a screenshot in a custom resolution (always 1:1 ratio) of the current view. Note that taking a screenshot will only work when seeing the piece live (click 'Open live' on fxhash), not on the mint page because of the sandboxed iframe.

Berlin, December 2021
@bgola

metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #479
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)

metadata.name: Morpheus #159
metadata.description:
A spinning, shapeshifting Morpheus which constantly changes form. 

3 Different Rotation types: 
Normal - 55% chance
Enhanced - 25% chance
Max - 20% chance

18 Palettes: 
15 with a 6% chance to appear
2 rare (Reds 4%, Greens 4%) 
1 very rare (Mono 2%)

Mouse click - or tap screen change all of the background colors

Some key functions: 
s - save output as png 
r - change from the standard rotation to a random different rotation amount
1 - randomly change the background color for the top left
2 - randomly change the background color for the top right	
3 - randomly change the background color for the bottom left
4 - randomly change the background color for the bottom right
c - Change the border and stroke colors of the Morpheus

Made in p5.js
P1xelboy 
May 2022

Windswept

Press 's' in live view to download a copy of your image.

You can add the URL parameter 'scale' to scale the size of the image for a higher resolution download (1600x2000 by default). For example, for a 3200x4000 image, add '&scale=2' to the end of the URL. 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 are valid inputs. (Warning: large numbers may not work depending on your hardware/browser and can produce a very large download file of ~100mb)
